To anyone interested,

We have had a lot of involvement with very large reaction mechanisms, 
and we have found that Chemkin does not perform well for our large 
mechanisms.  In cases where Chemkin cannot converge on an initial 
flame model, we can run the same flame on our own code, HCT, and then 
use that solution to get within the &quot;radius of convergence&quot; of the 
solution for Chemkin.  Our HCT code &quot;never fails to converge&quot;, which 
is largely due to its fairly primitive first-order, backward 
difference solution technique.  I suggest for people running either 
Cantera or Chemkin, if you can force either to run using this 
solution technique, you can probably get an answer, then refine the 
differencing in subsequent runs that start from the first set of 
solutions.  The first-order, backward differencing is supposed to be 
unconditionally stable if done properly, and our experience is that 
it works, even if you don&#39;t much like the solution.   I don&#39;t know if 
you can force this in Cantera, but it might be a valuable feature.

Charlie Westbrook




&gt;Dave,
&gt;
&gt;I have 50 or so converged laminar flame cases in Chemkin II Premix, most for
&gt;the experiments from the literature. Fuels are from methane to benzene,
&gt;low-p to atmospheric, simulated with a few detailed kinetic models from the
&gt;literature and with two of my own, ranging from 100 to 1200 reactions. (200
&gt;or so runs in total). All the flames have temperature profile from the
&gt;experiment. That&#39;s kind of a lot for the e-mail attachment.
&gt;
&gt;For about a third of those runs I have cantera solution as well, all with
&gt;multicomponent diffusion. Differences between cantera and CK Premix
&gt;solutions are  in most cases negligible. In few cases I examined in detail,
&gt;the differences originate from your improvenments in diffusion formulation.
&gt;
&gt;To my experience, Cantera (my Python premixed script) handles many a case on
&gt;which CK Premix gives up, but I have a handfull of cases that neither code
&gt;could find a solution for.
&gt;
&gt;Which address would you like the stuff sent to? I e-mailed you one of my
&gt;premixed Python/Cantera scripts to &#39;dgoodwin@...&#39; on May 11, but I
&gt;never heard back from you...
&gt;
&gt;Sincerely,
&gt;             Zoran
