&gt;
&gt;I am interested in doing some validation tests of the flame models in
&gt;Cantera, and would like to ask the assistance of anyone who routinely
&gt;runs flame simulations with the Chemkin version 2 codes PREMIX and/or
&gt;OPPDIFF.  What I am looking for are any converged, resolved flame
&gt;solutions from Chemkin 2, including:
&gt;
&gt;1) PREMIX or OPPDIFF input files
&gt;2) reaction mechanism and thermo data files in Chemkin format
&gt;3) computed species and temperature profiles in some text file format
&gt;
&gt;I am particularly interested in non-trivial flames with large
&gt;mechanisms or at atmospheric pressure or above (but any flame is
&gt;useful).  I would also like to have examples both with mixture-averaged
&gt;and multicomponent diffusion.  If you have this information for some
&gt;flame or flames, please send me a tar or zip file with the files listed
&gt;above.  I will take this information, generate the corresponding
&gt;Cantera input files + python script, and compare the computed profiles
&gt;(unless you want to do that too...).  I would plan on then sending back
&gt;to you the Cantera files, so that you could run a Cantera vs. Chemkin 2
&gt;timing comparison on the same machine.
&gt;
&gt;Based on previous comparisons of thermo properties, transport
&gt;properties, and kinetic rates, I fully expect excellent agreement in
&gt;the steady-state flame profiles, with substantial improvement in
&gt;performance.  But a head-to-head flame comparison would be very
&gt;interesting, and would provide assurance to users converting from the
&gt;Chemkin 2 codes that Cantera produces the same output, given the same
&gt;input.
&gt;
&gt;This will be most useful if we can get at least several flames from
&gt;different groups, running on different machines, etc.
&gt;If you have been wanting to contribute to the development of Cantera
&gt;and its acceptance by the combustion community, but aren&#39;t an expert in
&gt;C++/Python, etc., here&#39;s a good opportunity to do so!
&gt;
